IP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Madanpur ''' is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Rautahat District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of south-eastern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 1597 people living in 290 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1 |title=Nepal Census 2001 |work=Nepal's Village Development Committees |publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]] |accessdate=25 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012163506/http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1 |archivedate=12 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{Rautahat District}}\n\n{{Coord missing|Nepal}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Rautahat District]]\n\n\n{{Narayani-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Narayani-geo-stub}}, +{{Province2NP-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madanpur,_Rautahat"}
{"title_page": "Billericay", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =          England\n|static_image_name= Billericay High Street.jpg\n|static_image_caption=     Billericay High Street and St Mary Magdalen Church\n|official_name=     Billericay\n|civil_parish=      Billericay\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.628|0.4184|display=inline,title}}\n|population =       27,998\n|population_ref=        (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120704&c=Billericay&d=16&e=62&g=6422170&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1442843313680&enc=1|title=Town population 2011|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n|shire_district=    [[Borough of Basildon|Basildon]]\n|shire_county =     [[Essex]]\n|region=            East of England\n|constituency_westminster=      [[Basildon and Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|Basildon and Billericay]]\n|post_town=         BILLERICAY\n|postcode_district= CM11, CM12\n|postcode_area=     CM\n|dial_code=         01277\n|os_grid_reference= TQ675945\n}}\n'''Billericay''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-uk-Billericay.ogg|b|\u026a|l|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u026a|k|i\u02d0}} {{respell|BIL|\u0259|RIK|ee}}) is a town and [[civil parish]] in the [[Borough of Basildon]], Essex, England. It lies within the [[London Basin]] and constitutes a [[commuter town]] {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of [[Central London]]. The town has three secondary schools and a variety of open spaces. It is thought to have been occupied since the [[Bronze Age]].\n\n==History==\nSome of the earliest records of human occupation of Billericay are the [[burial mound]]s in [[Norsey Wood]]: evidence of occupation in the [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]]s. Evidence of [[Roman occupation of Britain|Roman occupation]] has been found at a number of locations in the town and there may have been a small cavalry fort at Blunts Wall.\n\nThe [[Saxons]] did not settle in the centre of Billericay. They established themselves two miles south, at [[Great Burstead]]. In the late 10th century it was known as 'Burhstede'. Billericay was not mentioned in the [[Domesday Book]], as it lay within Great Burstead. At this time the parish church for Billericay was at Great Burstead.\n\n===Origin of the name===\nBillericay (previously Billerica) is a well-known exception{{clarify|date=May 2018}} in the identification of the [[Toponymy of England|origins of English place-names]]. The name of the town was first recorded as \"Byllyrica\" in 1291. The urban settlement, which was within the manor and parish of [[Great Burstead]], was one of many founded in the late 13th century in an already densely populated rural landscape. \nSeveral suggestions for the origin of the place name include:\n* ''Villa Erica'' (Heather Villa), suggesting a Romano-British origin.\n* ''beller\u012bca'', a medieval [[Latin]] word meaning 'dyehouse or tanhouse'.<ref>'Oxford Dictionary of British Place-Names', A.D. Mills, Oxford University Press</ref>\n* ''billers'', a traditional name for [[watercress]], for which [[Bilbrook (disambiguation)|Bilbrook]] in Somerset and Staffordshire are named.  Watercress was farmed in Billericay springs during the 20th century.\n\nAlthough the precise etymology of the name is not known, England has other places named Billerica:\n* Billerica, Kent. A deserted town adjacent to the settlement of Court-up-Street by [[Port Lympne]]. Significantly this is adjacent to a Roman \"[[Saxon Shore]]\" fort as well as being on spring lines suitable for growing watercress.\n* Billerica Farm, near [[Upton Noble]], Somerset. Although this farm might be named after the other Billericas, the site is also close to springs suitable for farming watercress.\n\nThe Tudor antiquarian [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] believed the already-abandoned Billerica in Kent was a variant of ''Bellocastrum'', \u2018fair castle\u2019 in Latin. In Billericay there is a Roman fort at Blunt's Wall Farm; likewise \u2018[[Burh]]\u2019 gives is name to Great Burstead.\nThis suggests that a Romano-British place name was reused by the [[Anglo-Saxons]] following the [[end of Roman rule in Britain]].\n\n===Middle Ages===\n[[File:Norsey Woods, Billericay - geograph.org.uk - 48295.jpg|thumb|alt=Norsey Wood|Norsey woods]]\nIn the 13th and 14th centuries some pilgrims to Canterbury journeyed via Billericay. Some of them may have spent the night in Billericay before crossing the [[River Thames]] at [[Tilbury]]. This may account for the large number of inns in the town.\n\nBillericay's most notable historical episode was the [[Battle of Billericay]] during the [[Peasants' Revolt]] of 1381.\n\nThe [[John Wycliffe|Wycliffe preachers]] influenced the town. Four local people (Thomas Watts, Joan Hornes, Elizabeth Thackwell and Margaret Ellis) were [[burnt at the stake]]. Two other residents (Joan Potter and James Harris) were tortured for their faith during the reign of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]].\n\n===Pilgrim Fathers===\n\nA meeting of the [[Pilgrim Fathers]] prior to their sailing in the ''[[Mayflower]]'' is said to have taken place in Billericay, and many local names and much historical imagery reflect this: Mayflower House, Morris Men, Taxis, School, Hall. Sunnymede School's [[House system|houses]] were called Mayflower, Pilgrim, [[Chantry]] and Martin (after [[Christopher Martin (Mayflower Pilgrim)|Christopher Martin]], a Billericay merchant who travelled on the ''Mayflower'' as Ship's Governor).\n\nThe ''Mayflower'' set sail once the Pilgrim Fathers had all boarded and set to meet the ''Speedwell'' in the English Channel, the ''Speedwell'' sailing from the Netherlands. Unfortunately the ''Speedwell'' developed leaks and so the ships headed for the Devon coast to repair her, but this proved impossible, the ''Mayflower'' eventually sailing from Plymouth without her.\n\nFour people from Billericay were on board, including Christopher Martin. He and his wife Mary, along with Solomon Prowe and John Langemore, perished shortly after their arrival at [[Cape Cod]], [[Massachusetts]]. Christopher Martin remained and lived in Plymouth, Massachusetts, until his death in 1640.  His wife Mary (Mayflower) Martin perished in Plymouth in 1621. \n\nThe unfortunate fate of the would-be pioneers did not deter other inhabitants of Billericay from setting sail for the New World. The town of [[Billerica, Massachusetts]] was established in 1655 by colonists from Billericay and named after their home town in England.\n\n===Georgian and Victorian eras===\n\nIn the [[Georgian period]] many excellent examples of the period's houses were built in Billericay. One of those remaining today is Burghstead Lodge in High Street, which used to house the library. Sadly a number were demolished in the 1980s to make way for new developments, notable examples being on Western Road. \n\nIn the town, the Union Workhouse was built in 1840 to continue to implement the [[Poor Law]].  Parts of this building were later incorporated into what was St. Andrew's Hospital. The railway arrived in Billericay in 1889, being on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]] between London and [[Southend-on-Sea]].\n\n===The 20th century===\nIn 1916, during the First World War, a German Zeppelin airship was shot down during an aerial battle over Billericay.  During its fiery demise, it narrowly missed the High Street, crashing into a field off Greens Farm Lane. A plaque was erected at the site in 2016, to commemorate 100 years since the incident. \nParts of the aluminium frame can be seen at the [[Cater Museum]] in Billericay High Street.\nRecent research has indicated that this may be identified with the 'ghost Zeppelin' of Tonbridge which was allegedly seen floating over that town earlier in the day.\n\nSt. Andrew's Hospital, which was formerly the site of the town's Victorian [[workhouse]], continued to function as an important communal building.  From 1973, it housed the internationally renowned Regional Plastic Surgery and Burns unit until this was relocated to Broomfield Hospital, [[Chelmsford]] in April 1998.  After the relocation, most of the hospital was redeveloped into housing. The listed buildings remain intact but are now residential.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Lake Meadows, Billericay - geograph.org.uk - 48246.jpg|thumb|alt=Lake surrounded by trees in Billericay|The Boating Lake at Lake Meadows]]\n[[File:Mill_Meadows_-_Butchers_Field_-_Cowslip_-_20160411.jpg|thumb|Picture of Cowslip Wild Flower - Butchers Field - Mill Meadows, Billericay, Essex - 11 April 2016]]\nBillericay is within the [[London Basin]] and lies on a mixture of [[London clay]], [[London clay#Claygate Beds|Claygate Beds]] and [[Bagshot Beds]].  Near the High Street, there is a change in soil type from sandy to clay, which gives rise to local underground springs. Open spaces include [[Norsey Wood]], [[Mill Meadows, Billericay|Mill Meadows Nature Reserve]], Queen's Park Country Park, Sun Corner, [[Lake Meadows]], Hanningfield Reservoir and South Green. Billericay contains [[Billericay School]], [[Mayflower High School]] and [[St John's School (Billericay)|St John's School]].\n\nMill Meadows is a local nature reserve near the centre of Billericay, one of the finest ancient meadow systems in Essex. Centuries of grazing have created the ideal conditions for a wonderful diversity of wild flowers, fungi, insects and invertebrates, many of which are very rare. It also contains an area of 16.63 acres (6.73 ha) that has been declared as a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) for its unimproved neutral grassland.\n\n==Governance==\nBetween 1 July 1837 and 1 July 1939 Billericay was a registration district. Since 1974, the town has been part of the Basildon district. The registry office is located in Basildon, in the council offices. There is also the facility to register deaths in [[Basildon and Thurrock University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|Basildon Hospital]].<ref>[http://www.essexcc.gov.uk/vip8/ecc/ECCWebsite/dis/guc.jsp?channelOid=13563&guideOid=14832&guideContentOid=13933 Basildon District] \u2013 Essex County Council. Retrieved 22 September 2006.</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary===\nSince major boundary changes in Essex for the 2010 general election, Billericay has been part of the [[Basildon and Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|parliamentary constituency of Basildon and Billericay]], whose MP is [[John Baron (MP)|John Baron]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].  The town was previously represented by [[Teresa Gorman]] from 1987 to 2001, a Conservative rebel who had the [[whip (politics)|whip]] withdrawn for opposing the [[Maastricht Treaty]]. Her predecessor, the Conservative MP [[Harvey Proctor]], was also prominent in the news in 1987, when he was charged with indecency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/16/newsid_2524000/2524727.stm BBC: On this day 16 April 1987], Retrieved 7 September 2006.</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nBillericay is part of the [[Basildon (borough)|Basildon]] district. Basildon District Council is Conservative-controlled. Billericay is served by a town council of 20 members elected in 3 wards. There is also a youth town council, elected in schools around the town.<ref>[http://www.billericaytowncouncil.gov.uk/ Billericay Town Council]. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> The town council has powers related to local planning and finance, while the youth council has an annual budget of \u00a3500 to spend or invest in local services or entertainment.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060809062938/http://bytc.org/ Billericay Youth Town Council]. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref>\n\nBillericay parish was not formed until 1937; before then the area had been part of the ancient [[Great Burstead]] parish.<ref>[http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10235728 Vision of Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014529/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10235728 |date=30 September 2007 }} \u2013 Great Burstead parish ([http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10235728&c_id=10001043 historic map)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201441/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10235728&c_id=10001043 |date=27 September 2007 }}. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> In 1894 [[Billericay Rural District]] was created, which covered a wide area stretching as far as [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] and [[Pitsea]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201744/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10186389&c_id=10001043 Vision of Britain] \u2013 Billericay RD ([https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201221/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10186389&c_id=10001043 historic map)].  Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> In 1934 the core of this district around Basildon and Billericay became [[Billericay Urban District]], and in 1937 a Billericay civil parish was created covering the same area. The urban district, but not the parish, was renamed [[Basildon Urban District|Basildon]] in 1955. In 1974 the district was abolished and became the present-day [[Basildon (district)|Basildon district]].\n\n==Transport==\n\nBillericay is a part of the [[London commuter belt]].\n\nIt is served by [[Billericay railway station]] on the [[Abellio Greater Anglia]] [[Shenfield to Southend Line|route]] from [[Liverpool Street station]], in the [[City of London]], to [[Southend]].  The station connects to local bus routes.\n\nBillericay is close to two primary routes: the [[A12 road (Great Britain)|A12]] to the north and the [[A127 road|A127]] in the south.  The A176 provides a road link to Basildon to the south of Billericay, as well as to the A127.  The only secondary road in the town, the B1007, passes from just south of the town centre as Laindon Road, meets the [[A129 road|A129]] at Sun Corner and then continues northwards as Billericay's High Street and then Stock Road.  It continues north to the county town of Chelmsford.  Along its route is the village of Stock and an interchange to the A12.  The town is a destination on the A129, linking it to the neighbouring towns of Brentwood and Wickford.\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Billericay Cricket Club - geograph.org.uk - 49506.jpg|thumb|alt=Billericay Cricket Club|Billericay Cricket Club]]\n[[File:Billericay Town F.C. Main Stand.jpg|thumb|The clubhouse, main stand and The Cowshed at New Lodge, 2007]]\n\n*[[Billericay Town F.C.|Billericay Town]] Football Club\n*[[Billericay Rugby Football Club]]\n*[[Essex Spartans]]\n*Mayflower Archers\n*Billericay Striders Running Club\n\n==Culture and trivia==\n{{in popular culture|section|date=March 2020}} \nBillericay is served by a community radio station, [[Phoenix FM]], which is based in Brentwood.\n\nThe town was mentioned in the [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] song \"[[Billericay Dickie]]\".  \n\nBillericay is the setting of the [[BBC]] sitcom ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'' as the home of Gavin Shipman ([[Mathew Horne]]) and his parents; however, the actual filming took place in Wales.\n\nThe Cater Museum, a charity, is a local history museum containing artefacts recording the lives of people in the area. It is housed in an 18th and 19th century Grade II listed building in the High Street.\n\nThe Billericay Community Archive strives to record photos, memories and history relating to the town and surrounding areas on their website.\n\nBillericay's commercial cinema \"The Ritz\" closed its doors in 1971. However, in 2015, the Billericay Community Cinema was established. Less than a year after it started, the not-for-profit, volunteer-based group won a national award: the \"Best New Film Society\" at the Cinema for All Community Cinema Awards.\n\n==Twinning==\n\nBillericay is [[Town twinning|twinned]] with:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*{{Flag icon|USA}} [[Fishers, Indiana]], United States, since 1998<ref name=\"Fishers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/bta/fishers/twinning-ceremony-billericay/|title=Twinning Ceremony in Billericay |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n*{{Flag icon|USA}} [[Billerica, Massachusetts]], United States, since 1998<ref name=\"Billerica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericaytwinning.org.uk/|title=Billericay Mayflower Twinning Association |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n||\n*{{Flag icon|FRA}} [[Chauvigny]], France, since 2005<ref name=\"ChauvignyFr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chauvigny.fr/page.php?id=201|title=Le Comit\u00e9 de Jumelage|language=French|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819052058/http://www.chauvigny.fr/page.php?id=201|archivedate=19 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ChauvignyEng\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/bta/chauvigny/french-charter/|title=French Charter |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Refimprove section|date=October 2013}}\n*[[Neal Asher]], science fiction writer, born in Billericay\n* [[Francis Thomas Bacon]], engineer, born in Billericay<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-50801;jsessionid=B94E6057D8D67DC5F296AA4D391C1044|title=Bacon, Francis Thomas [Tom] (1904\u20131992), engineer and developer of the fuel cell {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/50801|access-date=10 February 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Lee Barnard]], footballer, went to school in Billericay\n* [[Peter Bone]], politician, born in Billericay\n* [[Nick Cater]], author and journalist in Australia, born in Billericay\n* [[Daniel Corbett]], TV weather forecaster, lived in Billericay as a child\n* [[Robert Denmark]], middle and long distance athlete \n* [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]], comedian, went to school and lives in Billericay\n* [[Mark Foster (swimmer)|Mark Foster]], swimmer, born in Billericay\n* [[Teresa Gorman]], politician, former Member of Parliament<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11831247/Teresa-Gorman-Tory-MP-obituary.html|title=Teresa Gorman, Tory MP - obituary|last=|first=|date=28 August 2015|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=16 February 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n* [[Lee Harrison]], footballer, born in Billericay\n* [[Chris Haywood]], actor/producer, born in Billericay\n* [[David Hopwood]], banker, born in Billericay\n* [[Ralph Izzard]],  journalist, born in Billericay\n* [[Perry McCarthy]], racing driver\n* [[Christopher Martin (Mayflower Pilgrim)|Christopher Martin]], Mayflower pilgrim, lived in Billericay\n* [[Alison Moyet]], pop singer, born in Billericay\n* [[Richard Osman]], TV personality (\"Pointless Friend\" on BBC show ''[[Pointless]]''), born in Billericay\n* [[Kevin Painter]], darts player, born in Billericay\n* [[Paul Parker (footballer)|Paul Parker]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-30000725.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105205258/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-30000725.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 November 2013|title=Parker reflects on career blighted by racist abuse ; Billericay resident was sent racially abusive letters by Everton fans|newspaper=Brentwood Gazette|date=2 November 2011}}</ref> was raised in Billericay and lived there when he became a professional footballer\n* [[Gemma Ray]], musician, singer, composer and producer, was raised in Billericay\n* [[Stewart Robson]], footballer, born in Billericay\n* [[Russell Tovey]], actor, has Billericay as his hometown<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/5001850/Russell-Tovey-interview-A-History-Boy-with-a-big-future.html\n|title=Russell Tovey interview: A History Boy with a big future |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=18 March 2009 | location=London | first=Byrony | last=Gordon}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Richardson]], gangster, lived in Billericay\n* [[Patrick W. Welch]], painter, born in Billericay\n* [[Charlie Wernham]], comedian and comedy actor, born and lives in Billericay\n* [[Ben Wheatley]], film director, born in Billericay\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.billericaysociety.co.uk/ The Billericay Society] \u2013 Retrieved 9 November 2006.\n\n{{Billericay}}\n{{Essex}}\n\n[[Category:Billericay| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Essex]]\n[[Category:Borough of Basildon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =          England\n|static_image_name= Billericay High Street.jpg\n|static_image_caption=     Billericay High Street and St Mary Magdalen Church\n|official_name=     Billericay\n|civil_parish=      Billericay\n|coordinates = {{coord|51.628|0.4184|display=inline,title}}\n|population =       27,998\n|population_ref=        (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120704&c=Billericay&d=16&e=62&g=6422170&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1442843313680&enc=1|title=Town population 2011|accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref>\n|shire_district=    [[Borough of Basildon|Basildon]]\n|shire_county =     [[Essex]]\n|region=            East of England\n|constituency_westminster=      [[Basildon and Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|Basildon and Billericay]]\n|post_town=         BILLERICAY\n|postcode_district= CM11, CM12\n|postcode_area=     CM\n|dial_code=         01277\n|os_grid_reference= TQ675945\n}}\n'''Billericay''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-uk-Billericay.ogg|b|\u026a|l|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u026a|k|i\u02d0}} {{respell|BIL|\u0259|RIK|ee}}) is a town and [[civil parish]] in the [[Borough of Basildon]], Essex, England. It lies within the [[London Basin]] and constitutes a [[commuter town]] {{convert|25|mi|km}} east of [[Central London]]. The town has three secondary schools and a variety of open spaces. It is thought to have been occupied since the [[Bronze Age]].\n\n==History==\nSome of the earliest records of human occupation of Billericay are the [[burial mound]]s in [[Norsey Wood]]: evidence of occupation in the [[Bronze Age|Bronze]] and [[Iron Age]]s. Evidence of [[Roman occupation of Britain|Roman occupation]] has been found at a number of locations in the town and there may have been a small cavalry fort at Blunts Wall.\n\nThe [[Saxons]] did not settle in the centre of Billericay. They established themselves two miles south, at [[Great Burstead]]. In the late 10th century it was known as 'Burhstede'. Billericay was not mentioned in the [[Domesday Book]], as it lay within Great Burstead. At this time the parish church for Billericay was at Great Burstead.\n\n===Origin of the name===\nBillericay (previously Billerica) is a well-known exception{{clarify|date=May 2018}} in the identification of the [[Toponymy of England|origins of English place-names]]. The name of the town was first recorded as \"Byllyrica\" in 1291. The urban settlement, which was within the manor and parish of [[Great Burstead]], was one of many founded in the late 13th century in an already densely populated rural landscape. \nSeveral suggestions for the origin of the place name include:\n* ''Villa Erica'' (Heather Villa), suggesting a Romano-British origin.\n* ''beller\u012bca'', a medieval [[Latin]] word meaning 'dyehouse or tanhouse'.<ref>'Oxford Dictionary of British Place-Names', A.D. Mills, Oxford University Press</ref>\n* ''billers'', a traditional name for [[watercress]], for which [[Bilbrook (disambiguation)|Bilbrook]] in Somerset and Staffordshire are named.  Watercress was farmed in Billericay springs during the 20th century.\n\nAlthough the precise etymology of the name is not known, England has other places named Billerica:\n* Billerica, Kent. A deserted town adjacent to the settlement of Court-up-Street by [[Port Lympne]]. Significantly this is adjacent to a Roman \"[[Saxon Shore]]\" fort as well as being on spring lines suitable for growing watercress.\n* Billerica Farm, near [[Upton Noble]], Somerset. Although this farm might be named after the other Billericas, the site is also close to springs suitable for farming watercress.\n\nThe Tudor antiquarian [[John Leland (antiquary)|John Leland]] believed the already-abandoned Billerica in Kent was a variant of ''Bellocastrum'', \u2018fair castle\u2019 in Latin. In Billericay there is a Roman fort at Blunt's Wall Farm; likewise \u2018[[Burh]]\u2019 gives is name to Great Burstead.\nThis suggests that a Romano-British place name was reused by the [[Anglo-Saxons]] following the [[end of Roman rule in Britain]].\n\n===Middle Ages===\n[[File:Norsey Woods, Billericay - geograph.org.uk - 48295.jpg|thumb|alt=Norsey Wood|Norsey woods]]\nIn the 13th and 14th centuries some pilgrims to Canterbury journeyed via Billericay. Some of them may have spent the night in Billericay before crossing the [[River Thames]] at [[Tilbury]]. This may account for the large number of inns in the town.\n\nBillericay's most notable historical episode was the [[Battle of Billericay]] during the [[Peasants' Revolt]] of 1381.\n\nThe [[John Wycliffe|Wycliffe preachers]] influenced the town. Four local people (Thomas Watts, Joan Hornes, Elizabeth Thackwell and Margaret Ellis) were [[burnt at the stake]]. Two other residents (Joan Potter and James Harris) were tortured for their faith during the reign of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]].\n\n===Pilgrim Fathers===\n\nA meeting of the [[Pilgrim Fathers]] prior to their sailing in the ''[[Mayflower]]'' is said to have taken place in Billericay, and many local names and much historical imagery reflect this: Mayflower House, Morris Men, Taxis, School, Hall. Sunnymede School's [[House system|houses]] were called Mayflower, Pilgrim, [[Chantry]] and Martin (after [[Christopher Martin (Mayflower Pilgrim)|Christopher Martin]], a Billericay merchant who travelled on the ''Mayflower'' as Ship's Governor).\n\nThe ''Mayflower'' set sail once the Pilgrim Fathers had all boarded and set to meet the ''Speedwell'' in the English Channel, the ''Speedwell'' sailing from the Netherlands. Unfortunately the ''Speedwell'' developed leaks and so the ships headed for the Devon coast to repair her, but this proved impossible, the ''Mayflower'' eventually sailing from Plymouth without her.\n\nFour people from Billericay were on board, including Christopher Martin. He and his wife Mary, along with Solomon Prowe and John Langemore, perished shortly after their arrival at [[Cape Cod]], [[Massachusetts]]. Christopher Martin remained and lived in Plymouth, Massachusetts, until his death in 1640.  His wife Mary (Mayflower) Martin perished in Plymouth in 1621. \n\nThe unfortunate fate of the would-be pioneers did not deter other inhabitants of Billericay from setting sail for the New World. The town of [[Billerica, Massachusetts]] was established in 1655 by colonists from Billericay and named after their home town in England.\n\n===Georgian and Victorian eras===\n\nIn the [[Georgian period]] many excellent examples of the period's houses were built in Billericay. One of those remaining today is Burghstead Lodge in High Street, which used to house the library. Sadly a number were demolished in the 1980s to make way for new developments, notable examples being on Western Road. \n\nIn the town, the Union Workhouse was built in 1840 to continue to implement the [[Poor Law]].  Parts of this building were later incorporated into what was St. Andrew's Hospital. The railway arrived in Billericay in 1889, being on the [[Great Eastern Main Line]] between London and [[Southend-on-Sea]].\n\n===The 20th century===\nIn 1916, during the First World War, a German Zeppelin airship was shot down during an aerial battle over Billericay.  During its fiery demise, it narrowly missed the High Street, crashing into a field off Greens Farm Lane. A plaque was erected at the site in 2016, to commemorate 100 years since the incident. \nParts of the aluminium frame can be seen at the [[Cater Museum]] in Billericay High Street.\nRecent research has indicated that this may be identified with the 'ghost Zeppelin' of Tonbridge which was allegedly seen floating over that town earlier in the day.\n\nSt. Andrew's Hospital, which was formerly the site of the town's Victorian [[workhouse]], continued to function as an important communal building.  From 1973, it housed the internationally renowned Regional Plastic Surgery and Burns unit until this was relocated to Broomfield Hospital, [[Chelmsford]] in April 1998.  After the relocation, most of the hospital was redeveloped into housing. The listed buildings remain intact but are now residential.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Lake Meadows, Billericay - geograph.org.uk - 48246.jpg|thumb|alt=Lake surrounded by trees in Billericay|The Boating Lake at Lake Meadows]]\n[[File:Mill_Meadows_-_Butchers_Field_-_Cowslip_-_20160411.jpg|thumb|Picture of Cowslip Wild Flower - Butchers Field - Mill Meadows, Billericay, Essex - 11 April 2016]]\nBillericay is within the [[London Basin]] and lies on a mixture of [[London clay]], [[London clay#Claygate Beds|Claygate Beds]] and [[Bagshot Beds]].  Near the High Street, there is a change in soil type from sandy to clay, which gives rise to local underground springs. Open spaces include [[Norsey Wood]], [[Mill Meadows, Billericay|Mill Meadows Nature Reserve]], Queen's Park Country Park, Sun Corner, [[Lake Meadows]], Hanningfield Reservoir and South Green. Billericay contains [[Billericay School]], [[Mayflower High School]] and [[St John's School (Billericay)|St John's School]].\n\nMill Meadows is a local nature reserve near the centre of Billericay, one of the finest ancient meadow systems in Essex. Centuries of grazing have created the ideal conditions for a wonderful diversity of wild flowers, fungi, insects and invertebrates, many of which are very rare. It also contains an area of 16.63 acres (6.73 ha) that has been declared as a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) for its unimproved neutral grassland.\n\n==Governance==\nBetween 1 July 1837 and 1 July 1939 Billericay was a registration district. Since 1974, the town has been part of the Basildon district. The registry office is located in Basildon, in the council offices. There is also the facility to register deaths in [[Basildon and Thurrock University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|Basildon Hospital]].<ref>[http://www.essexcc.gov.uk/vip8/ecc/ECCWebsite/dis/guc.jsp?channelOid=13563&guideOid=14832&guideContentOid=13933 Basildon District] \u2013 Essex County Council. Retrieved 22 September 2006.</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary===\nSince major boundary changes in Essex for the 2010 general election, Billericay has been part of the [[Basildon and Billericay (UK Parliament constituency)|parliamentary constituency of Basildon and Billericay]], whose MP is [[John Baron (MP)|John Baron]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].  The town was previously represented by [[Teresa Gorman]] from 1987 to 2001, a Conservative rebel who had the [[whip (politics)|whip]] withdrawn for opposing the [[Maastricht Treaty]]. Her predecessor, the Conservative MP [[Harvey Proctor]], was also prominent in the news in 1987, when he was charged with indecency.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/16/newsid_2524000/2524727.stm BBC: On this day 16 April 1987], Retrieved 7 September 2006.</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nBillericay is part of the [[Basildon (borough)|Basildon]] district. Basildon District Council is Conservative-controlled. Billericay is served by a town council of 20 members elected in 3 wards. There is also a youth town council, elected in schools around the town.<ref>[http://www.billericaytowncouncil.gov.uk/ Billericay Town Council]. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> The town council has powers related to local planning and finance, while the youth council has an annual budget of \u00a3500 to spend or invest in local services or entertainment.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060809062938/http://bytc.org/ Billericay Youth Town Council]. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref>\n\nBillericay parish was not formed until 1937; before then the area had been part of the ancient [[Great Burstead]] parish.<ref>[http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10235728 Vision of Britain] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930014529/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10235728 |date=30 September 2007 }} \u2013 Great Burstead parish ([http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10235728&c_id=10001043 historic map)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201441/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10235728&c_id=10001043 |date=27 September 2007 }}. Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> In 1894 [[Billericay Rural District]] was created, which covered a wide area stretching as far as [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood]] and [[Pitsea]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201744/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10186389&c_id=10001043 Vision of Britain] \u2013 Billericay RD ([https://web.archive.org/web/20070927201221/http://vision.edina.ac.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10186389&c_id=10001043 historic map)].  Retrieved 9 November 2006.</ref> In 1934 the core of this district around Basildon and Billericay became [[Billericay Urban District]], and in 1937 a Billericay civil parish was created covering the same area. The urban district, but not the parish, was renamed [[Basildon Urban District|Basildon]] in 1955. In 1974 the district was abolished and became the present-day [[Basildon (district)|Basildon district]].\n\n==Transport==\n\nBillericay is a part of the [[London commuter belt]].\n\nIt is served by [[Billericay railway station]] on the [[Abellio Greater Anglia]] [[Shenfield to Southend Line|route]] from [[Liverpool Street station]], in the [[City of London]], to [[Southend]].  The station connects to local bus routes.\n\nBillericay is close to two primary routes: the [[A12 road (Great Britain)|A12]] to the north and the [[A127 road|A127]] in the south.  The A176 provides a road link to Basildon to the south of Billericay, as well as to the A127.  The only secondary road in the town, the B1007, passes from just south of the town centre as Laindon Road, meets the [[A129 road|A129]] at Sun Corner and then continues northwards as Billericay's High Street and then Stock Road.  It continues north to the county town of Chelmsford.  Along its route is the village of Stock and an interchange to the A12.  The town is a destination on the A129, linking it to the neighbouring towns of Brentwood and Wickford.\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Billericay Cricket Club - geograph.org.uk - 49506.jpg|thumb|alt=Billericay Cricket Club|Billericay Cricket Club]]\n[[File:Billericay Town F.C. Main Stand.jpg|thumb|The clubhouse, main stand and The Cowshed at New Lodge, 2007]]\n\n*[[Billericay Town F.C.|Billericay Town]] Football Club\n*[[Billericay Rugby Football Club]]\n*[[Essex Spartans]]\n*Mayflower Archers\n*Billericay Striders Running Club\n\n==Culture and trivia==\n{{in popular culture|section|date=March 2020}} \nBillericay is served by a community radio station, [[Phoenix FM]], which is based in Brentwood.\n\nThe town was mentioned in the [[Ian Dury and the Blockheads]] song \"[[Billericay Dickie]]\".  \n\nBillericay is the setting of the [[BBC]] sitcom ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'' as the home of Gavin Shipman ([[Mathew Horne]]) and his parents; however, the actual filming took place in Wales.\n\nThe Cater Museum, a charity, is a local history museum containing artefacts recording the lives of people in the area. It is housed in an 18th and 19th century Grade II listed building in the High Street.\n\nThe Billericay Community Archive strives to record photos, memories and history relating to the town and surrounding areas on their website.\n\nBillericay's commercial cinema \"The Ritz\" closed its doors in 1971. However, in 2015, the Billericay Community Cinema was established. Less than a year after it started, the not-for-profit, volunteer-based group won a national award: the \"Best New Film Society\" at the Cinema for All Community Cinema Awards.\n\n==Twinning==\n\nBillericay is [[Town twinning|twinned]] with:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*{{Flag icon|USA}} [[Fishers, Indiana]], United States, since 1998<ref name=\"Fishers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/bta/fishers/twinning-ceremony-billericay/|title=Twinning Ceremony in Billericay |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n*{{Flag icon|USA}} [[Billerica, Massachusetts]], United States, since 1998<ref name=\"Billerica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billericaytwinning.org.uk/|title=Billericay Mayflower Twinning Association |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n||\n*{{Flag icon|FRA}} [[Chauvigny]], France, since 2005<ref name=\"ChauvignyFr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chauvigny.fr/page.php?id=201|title=Le Comit\u00e9 de Jumelage|language=French|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819052058/http://www.chauvigny.fr/page.php?id=201|archivedate=19 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ChauvignyEng\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essexinfo.net/bta/chauvigny/french-charter/|title=French Charter |publisher=|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Refimprove section|date=October 2013}}\n*[[Neal Asher]], science fiction writer, born in Billericay\n* [[Francis Thomas Bacon]], engineer, born in Billericay<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-50801;jsessionid=B94E6057D8D67DC5F296AA4D391C1044|title=Bacon, Francis Thomas [Tom] (1904\u20131992), engineer and developer of the fuel cell {{!}} Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=www.oxforddnb.com|language=