ician, singer, composer and producer, was raised in Billericay\n* [[Stewart Robson]], footballer, born in Billericay\n* [[Russell Tovey]], actor, has Billericay as his hometown<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/drama/5001850/Russell-Tovey-interview-A-History-Boy-with-a-big-future.html\n|title=Russell Tovey interview: A History Boy with a big future |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 March 2009 |accessdate=18 March 2009 | location=London | first=Byrony | last=Gordon}}</ref>\n* [[Charlie Richardson]], gangster, lived in Billericay\n* [[Patrick W. Welch]], painter, born in Billericay\n* [[Charlie Wernham]], comedian and comedy actor, born and lives in Billericay\n* [[Ben Wheatley]], film director, born in Billericay\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n*[http://www.billericaysociety.co.uk/ The Billericay Society] \u2013 Retrieved 9 November 2006.\n\n{{Billericay}}\n{{Essex}}\n\n[[Category:Billericay| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in the Borough of Basildon]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Essex]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Essex]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:don't need a non-standard category for only 3 pages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billericay"}
{"title_page": "James Chau", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=October 2010|reason=cleanup references}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''James Chau''' (Chinese: \u5468\u67f3\u5efa\u6210 ''Zh\u014duli\u01d4'' ''Ji\u00e0nch\u00e9ng''{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}) who was born on 11 December 1977,<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\">{{cite web |url=http://www.james-chau.com/about/ |title=About |publisher=James Chau |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202045214/http://www.james-chau.com/about/ |archive-date=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a [[journalist]], television presenter, and United Nations [[Goodwill Ambassador]]. He anchors the main evening news on [[China Central Television]], which broadcasts from [[Beijing]] to more than 80 countries, and reports live on location worldwide.<ref>http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/St%20Edmund's%20Edition%20No.%203.pdf{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As a correspondent, he has covered breaking news on the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Asian tsunami]]<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/goingglobal-gg4-speakers-james-chau.htm |title=James Chau \u2013 Speakers \u2013 Going Global 4 |publisher=British Council |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and global [[SARS]] outbreak,<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\"/> and has interviewed world figures: [[UN Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDX2GHRnqXs ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609034724/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDX2GHRnqXs |date=9 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Nobel Laureate]] [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h3lfpa4eTZM |title=James Chau Interviews... Noble Prize Winner Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[King Constantine II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/program/worldinsight/20051228/101649.shtml |title=CCTV International |publisher=Cctv.com |date=28 December 2005 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is one of the few journalists to have interviewed Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] and mathematics teacher [[Anand Kumar]].,<ref name=\"jameschau2004\">{{cite web|url=http://sites.google.com/site/jameschau2004/ |title=jameschau2004 |publisher=Google  |date=8 June 2006 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"english.cntv.cn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/education/in-china-super-30-maths-wizard-sees-a-lesson-for-india/article2889936.ece|title=In China, 'Super 30' Maths wizard sees a lesson for India |accessdate= 14 February 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|first=Ananth|last=Krishnan|date=14 February 2012}}</ref> In 2009, he was appointed by the United Nations as China's first [[UNAIDS]] Goodwill Ambassador.<ref name=\"unaids.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/UNAIDS_National_Goodwill_Amb_JamesChau.asp |title=Partnerships Department |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nChau was born in [[England]] and educated at [[City of London School]]<ref>[http://jcc.org.uk/members-news/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905220813/http://jcc.org.uk/members-news/ |date=5 September 2009 }}</ref> and [[St. Edmund's College, University of Cambridge]], where he was ''[[Varsity (Cambridge)|Varsity]]'' News Features Editor.<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\">{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/reporter/james/un/index.shtml |title=CCTV reporter James Chau in UN Millennium summit \u2013 Interview Video |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He also studied piano at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] under Professor Graeme Humphrey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.123people.com/s/graeme+humphrey |title=Graeme Humphrey \u2013 Email, Address, Phone numbers, everything! |publisher=123people.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In interviews, he has cited the photographer [[Lord Snowdon]] for encouraging him as a writer,<ref name=\"shmag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.shmag.cn/feature/first_person_james_chau |title=SH Magazine: Shanghai restaurants, events and nightlife &#124; SH Magazine Online |publisher=Shmag.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303190339/http://www.shmag.cn/feature/first_person_james_chau |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and guiding him to his first journalistic internship at ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''. His parents were born in Indonesia and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lt.radio86.com/node/27793 |title=I Am Broadcasting From China - All about China &#124; Radio86.com |publisher=Lt.radio86.com |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Television ==\nAfter graduating from Cambridge, and interning at ''Vogue'' and [[Mirror Group Newspapers]],<ref name=\"shmag\"/> he moved to [[Hong Kong]] for his first newsroom position. From 2001 he was a reporter and later an anchor at [[TVB Pearl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/C12203/01/index.shtml |title=CCTV-English Channel-James Chau |publisher=Cctv.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> His first major story was in Washington where Hong Kong Chief Executive [[Tung Chee-Hwa]] met for talks with U.S. President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/C12203/20040430/101784.shtml |title=CCTV-English Channel-James Chau |publisher=Cctv.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> Chau returned to the White House a year later with Chinese leader [[Hu Jintao]] and was the only foreign journalist to cover all seven cities in what was the incoming President's debut overseas tour.<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\"/> During a reporting assignment to the [[World Trade Organization]] in Geneva on 11 September 2001, he flew to London to cover the international reaction to the terrorist attack on the World Trade Center in New York.<ref>http://www.icaap9.org/userfiles/Bio%20-%20James%20Chau.pdf</ref> While promoted to anchor the news, he continued to report on the bird flu outbreak, the [[Doha Ministerial Conference]] where China was accepted as a WTO member, and the SARS pandemic that took him to outbreak areas in Hong Kong, Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur.<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\"/>\n\nChau joined China Central Television in 2004,<ref name=\"jameschau2004\"/> where he features primarily as a main presenter on the 24-hour CCTV News English-language station. Since April 2010, he also co-fronts the channel's flagship ''China 24'' show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/program/china24/01/index.shtml |title=China Central Television |publisher=English.cntv.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is one of the first foreign anchors to anchor the evening program for the state broadcaster that, across its various channels combined, draws an audience share of 1.2 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/results?start=30&endeca=1&return=endeca&D=11%2F05%2F2008&Nty=1&N=4294966457&Ns=P_Ranking%7c1 |title=November 5, 2008 &#124; Fast Facts |publisher=Adage.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> His breaking stories include the suicide of former South Korean President [[Roh Moo-hyun]], [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|Sichuan earthquake]], and the [[Indian General Election, 2009|2009 Indian elections]]. In the run-up to the Beijing Olympics, he taped a television special on the Great Wall of China with the Australian actress and singer, [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jmnM-p4v-9M |title=James Chau Interviews... Olivia Newton-John |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> During the Games, he anchored the morning show for the official Olympic broadcaster.<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\"/> His two-hour coverage of the live standoff where eight Hong Kong tourists died in the [[Manila hostage crisis]] was noted in the ''[[Guardian newspaper|Guardian]]'' for the openness of this coverage in the Chinese state media.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jonathan Watts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/aug/23/manila-bus-siege-hostages-philippines-china |title=At least eight dead in Philippines as siege ends with police storming bus &#124; World news |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=25 October 2011 |date=23 August 2010}}</ref> He continues to report on location for the Asian tsunami in Indonesia, [[International AIDS Conference]] in Vienna, and [[UN General Assembly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/reporter/james/index.shtml |title=James Chau, UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador for China \u2013 CCTV Host and Reporter |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[Millennium Development Goals]] Summit in New York.<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/>\n\nHe writes a newspaper column for the state-run tabloid ''[[Global Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/commentary/2010-09/577798_2.html |title=Aids won't wait for the recession to finish \u2013 GlobalTimes |publisher=Opinion.globaltimes.cn |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720164045/http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/commentary/2010-09/577798_2.html |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/foreign-view/2010-08/568525.html |title=Manila's botched bus rescue leaves a bad taste behind |work=Global Times |date=30 August 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720164022/http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/foreign-view/2010-08/568525.html |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador ==\nChau has been described as one of China's leading AIDS activists.<ref name=\"unaids.org.cn\">http://unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2009121808551558.pdf</ref><ref>http://unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2009111213035034.pdf</ref> He came under the early mentorship of Belgian scientist [[Peter Piot]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shenzhen.urbanatomy.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=302:secrets-a-lies-cctvs-james-chau&catid=144:features&Itemid=12 |title=that's PRD &#124; Listings, Events, Reviews, Jobs |publisher=Shenzhen.urbanatomy.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> who co-discovered the [[Ebola]] virus, and has traveled on health missions to India, Norway, Indonesia, and the United States.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/> In August 2009, the United Nations announced his appointment as its first UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador on the Chinese Mainland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/excl/20090814/110009.shtml |title=CCTV news anchor James Chau nominated \"UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador\" CCTV-International |publisher=Cctv.com |date=14 August 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> joining [[Naomi Watts]], [[Michael Ballack]] and [[Princess Stephanie of Monaco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/default.asp |title=Partnerships Department |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In April 2010, his first show as presenter of the new ''China 24'' program was headlined by China's lifting of the HIV-related travel ban,.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uaat-XhJoNw |title=James Chau Reports... China Lifts HIV Travel Ban |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador, he has been featured in ''[[GQ]]'' and ''[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]]'',<ref name=\"unaids.org.cn\"/> and partners with leading Chinese internet portal, [[Sohu.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gongyi.sohu.com/20091128/n268541563.shtml |title=\u641c\u72d0\u4e3e\u529e\u827e\u6ecb\u75c5\u65e5\u4e3b\u9898\u6d3b\u52a8 \u5173\u6ce8\u53d7\u827e\u6ecb\u5f71\u54cd\u5b69\u5b50-\u516c\u76ca\u9891\u9053 |publisher=Gongyi.sohu.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In 2008, he was named to the inaugural Young Leaders Summit at the [[Google]] headquarters,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/youngleaderssummit |title=Our2031 \u2013 Blog |publisher=Aids2031 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230327/http://www.aids2031.org/youngleaderssummit |archive-date=24 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and to the second edition hosted in Oslo by [[Crown Princess Mette-Marit of Norway]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/2009%20young%20leaders%20summit%20meeting%20report.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723171007/http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/2009%20young%20leaders%20summit%20meeting%20report.pdf |archive-date=23 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Chau chaired the closing session of the 2009 International Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific in Bali, and hosted the opening televised town hall event of the 2010 International AIDS Conference in Vienna<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/archive/2010/20100715_TownHall.asp |title=Join UNAIDS and IAS at Town Hall on reshaping the future of AIDS |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> with singer and activist [[Annie Lennox]], UNAIDS Executive Director [[Michel Sidib\u00e9]], U.S. Congresswoman [[Barbara Lee]], and South African Deputy President [[Kgalema Motlanthe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2010-08/03/content_132698.htm?div=-1 |title=\u4e16\u754c\u827e\u6ecb\u75c5\u5927\u4f1a\u65b0\u8fdb\u5c55 -\u5065\u5eb7\u516c\u793e\u00b7\u5173\u6ce8-\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7535\u5b50\u62a5 |publisher=Epaper.bjnews.com.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalhealth.kff.org/AIDS2010/July-18/Towards-a-Paradigm-Shift-in-HIV-Treatment.aspx |title=Towards a Paradigm Shift in HIV Treatment and Prevention \u2013 Kaiser Global Health |publisher=Globalhealth.kff.org |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> At the same conference, he moderated the innovative financing debate between [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria|Global Fund]] chief [[Michel Kazatchkine]] and former French Foreign Minister [[Philippe Douste-Blazy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalhealth.kff.org/AIDS2010/July-21/Funding-Global-Health.aspx |title=Funding Global Health: Can Innovative Mechanisms Save the Day? |publisher=Kaiser Global Health |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nChau is a member of aids2031<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/asian_economies_in_rapid_transition_hiv_now_and_through_2031%5B2%5D.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723171054/http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/asian_economies_in_rapid_transition_hiv_now_and_through_2031%5B2%5D.pdf |archive-date=23 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Fashion Against AIDS|Designers Against AIDS]].\n\n== Interviews ==\nHe sat down with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe during the 2010 UN General Assembly,<ref name=\"english.cntv.cn\"/> and at the same event with United Nations Secretary General Ban Ki-moon,<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> Indian Foreign Secretary [[Nirupama Rao]],<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> Polish Foreign Minister [[Rados\u0142aw Sikorski]],<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> and South African Health Minister [[Aaron Motsoaledi]]. His other interview guests are Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Tun Razak]], Indonesian Trade Minister [[Mari Pangestu]], former [[King Constantine II of Greece]], [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]], former Botswanan President [[Festus Mogae]],<ref>http://www.unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2010081913251993.doc</ref> UNAIDS Executive Director [[Michel Sidib\u00e9]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-vq0YxTj6ts |title=James Chau Interviews... UN Under Secretary-General Michel Sidib\u00e9 |publisher=YouTube |date=30 September 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eVURMqeCvEc |title=James Chau Live... 2010 International AIDS Conference |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> U.S. Assistant Secretary for Health [[Howard Koh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSAokwXeAXo |title=James Chau Interviews... U.S. Assistant Secretary for Health Howard Koh |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and First Lady of Georgia [[Sandra Roelofs|Sandra Saakashvili]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bm51g5TIECc |title=James Chau Interviews... First Lady of Georgia Sandra Saakashvili |publisher=YouTube |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> From the arts, he profiled Freedom Towers architect [[Daniel Libeskind]], and in fashion, [[Jimmy Choo]], [[Vivienne Tam]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.james-chau.com/podcast/ |title=Podcast |publisher=James Chau |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and Jason Wu. His interview with Chinese military singer [[Peng Liyuan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gJKSOsMqKvc |title=James Chau Interviews... Chinese military general Peng Liyuan |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> was a rare television exclusive, and he has also spoken on camera to [[Crown Prince Haakon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rir705KKi3s |title=HRH Haakon and James Chau on Dignity and Respect \u2013 HIV/AIDS (Part 1) |publisher=YouTube |date=24 June 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[Crown Princess Mette-Marit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0g3gAJ3geRU |title=HRH Mette-Marit and James Chau (Part 3) |publisher=YouTube |date=25 June 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> of Norway, and French virologist [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> whose co-discovery of HIV won her the Nobel Prize in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2008/press.html |title=The 2008 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Nobelprize.org |date=6 October 2008 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Other ==\nHe is a [[Freeman of the City of London]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tieba.baidu.com/f?kz=87336474 |title=Guild of Scholars of the City of London_\u5468\u5efa\u6210\u5427_\u8d34\u5427 |publisher=Tieba.baidu.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> a [[National Press Foundation]] Fellow.,<ref>{{cite web |last=Meyers |first=Bob |url=http://nationalpress.org/blogs/aids/category/j2j/ |title=J2J &#124; NPF Helpdesk &#124; National Press Foundation |publisher=Nationalpress.org |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229235509/http://nationalpress.org/blogs/aids/category/j2j/ |archive-date=29 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a representative of the [[British Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/goingglobal-gg4-speakers-a-z.htm |title=A to Z \u2013 Session speakers- Going Global 4 |publisher=British Council |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.james-chau.com Official website]\n* [http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/default.asp UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassadors]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chau, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chinese columnists]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:China Central Television]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=October 2010|reason=cleanup references}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''James Chau''' (Chinese: \u5468\u67f3\u5efa\u6210 ''Zh\u014duli\u01d4'' ''Ji\u00e0nch\u00e9ng''{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}) who was born on 11 December 1977,<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\">{{cite web |url=http://www.james-chau.com/about/ |title=About |publisher=James Chau |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202045214/http://www.james-chau.com/about/ |archive-date=2 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is a [[journalist]], television presenter, and United Nations [[Goodwill Ambassador]]. He anchors the main evening news on [[China Central Television]], which broadcasts from [[Beijing]] to more than 80 countries, and reports live on location worldwide.<ref>http://www.st-edmunds.cam.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/St%20Edmund's%20Edition%20No.%203.pdf{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> As a correspondent, he has covered breaking news on the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Asian tsunami]]<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/goingglobal-gg4-speakers-james-chau.htm |title=James Chau \u2013 Speakers \u2013 Going Global 4 |publisher=British Council |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and global [[SARS]] outbreak,<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\"/> and has interviewed world figures: [[UN Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]],<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDX2GHRnqXs ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609034724/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vDX2GHRnqXs |date=9 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Nobel Laureate]] [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h3lfpa4eTZM |title=James Chau Interviews... Noble Prize Winner Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[King Constantine II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/program/worldinsight/20051228/101649.shtml |title=CCTV International |publisher=Cctv.com |date=28 December 2005 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is one of the few journalists to have interviewed Zimbabwean President [[Robert Mugabe]] and mathematics teacher [[Anand Kumar]].,<ref name=\"jameschau2004\">{{cite web|url=http://sites.google.com/site/jameschau2004/ |title=jameschau2004 |publisher=Google  |date=8 June 2006 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"english.cntv.cn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/education/in-china-super-30-maths-wizard-sees-a-lesson-for-india/article2889936.ece|title=In China, 'Super 30' Maths wizard sees a lesson for India |accessdate= 14 February 2012 | location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|first=Ananth|last=Krishnan|date=14 February 2012}}</ref> In 2009, he was appointed by the United Nations as China's first [[UNAIDS]] Goodwill Ambassador.<ref name=\"unaids.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/UNAIDS_National_Goodwill_Amb_JamesChau.asp |title=Partnerships Department |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nChau was born in [[England]] and educated at [[City of London School]]<ref>[http://jcc.org.uk/members-news/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905220813/http://jcc.org.uk/members-news/ |date=5 September 2009 }}</ref> and [[St. Edmund's College, University of Cambridge]], where he was ''[[Varsity (Cambridge)|Varsity]]'' News Features Editor.<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\">{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/reporter/james/un/index.shtml |title=CCTV reporter James Chau in UN Millennium summit \u2013 Interview Video |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He also studied piano at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] under Professor Graeme Humphrey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.123people.com/s/graeme+humphrey |title=Graeme Humphrey \u2013 Email, Address, Phone numbers, everything! |publisher=123people.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In interviews, he has cited the photographer [[Lord Snowdon]] for encouraging him as a writer,<ref name=\"shmag\">{{cite web |url=http://www.shmag.cn/feature/first_person_james_chau |title=SH Magazine: Shanghai restaurants, events and nightlife &#124; SH Magazine Online |publisher=Shmag.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303190339/http://www.shmag.cn/feature/first_person_james_chau |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and guiding him to his first journalistic internship at ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''. His parents were born in Indonesia and Hong Kong.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lt.radio86.com/node/27793 |title=I Am Broadcasting From China - All about China &#124; Radio86.com |publisher=Lt.radio86.com |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Television ==\nAfter graduating from Cambridge, and interning at ''Vogue'' and [[Mirror Group Newspapers]],<ref name=\"shmag\"/> he moved to [[Hong Kong]] for his first newsroom position. From 2001 he was a reporter and later an anchor at [[TVB Pearl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/C12203/01/index.shtml |title=CCTV-English Channel-James Chau |publisher=Cctv.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> His first major story was in Washington where Hong Kong Chief Executive [[Tung Chee-Hwa]] met for talks with U.S. President [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/C12203/20040430/101784.shtml |title=CCTV-English Channel-James Chau |publisher=Cctv.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> Chau returned to the White House a year later with Chinese leader [[Hu Jintao]] and was the only foreign journalist to cover all seven cities in what was the incoming President's debut overseas tour.<ref name=\"British Council GG4 speakers\"/> During a reporting assignment to the [[World Trade Organization]] in Geneva on 11 September 2001, he flew to London to cover the international reaction to the terrorist attack on the World Trade Center in New York.<ref>http://www.icaap9.org/userfiles/Bio%20-%20James%20Chau.pdf</ref> While promoted to anchor the news, he continued to report on the bird flu outbreak, the [[Doha Ministerial Conference]] where China was accepted as a WTO member, and the SARS pandemic that took him to outbreak areas in Hong Kong, Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur.<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\"/>\n\nChau joined China Central Television in 2004,<ref name=\"jameschau2004\"/> where he features primarily as a main presenter on the 24-hour CCTV News English-language station. Since April 2010, he also co-fronts the channel's flagship ''China 24'' show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/program/china24/01/index.shtml |title=China Central Television |publisher=English.cntv.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is one of the first foreign anchors to anchor the evening program for the state broadcaster that, across its various channels combined, draws an audience share of 1.2 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adage.com/results?start=30&endeca=1&return=endeca&D=11%2F05%2F2008&Nty=1&N=4294966457&Ns=P_Ranking%7c1 |title=November 5, 2008 &#124; Fast Facts |publisher=Adage.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> His breaking stories include the suicide of former South Korean President [[Roh Moo-hyun]], [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|Sichuan earthquake]], and the [[Indian General Election, 2009|2009 Indian elections]]. In the run-up to the Beijing Olympics, he taped a television special on the Great Wall of China with the Australian actress and singer, [[Olivia Newton-John]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jmnM-p4v-9M |title=James Chau Interviews... Olivia Newton-John |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> During the Games, he anchored the morning show for the official Olympic broadcaster.<ref name=\"james-chau.com about\"/> His two-hour coverage of the live standoff where eight Hong Kong tourists died in the [[Manila hostage crisis]] was noted in the ''[[Guardian newspaper|Guardian]]'' for the openness of this coverage in the Chinese state media.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jonathan Watts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/aug/23/manila-bus-siege-hostages-philippines-china |title=At least eight dead in Philippines as siege ends with police storming bus &#124; World news |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=25 October 2011 |date=23 August 2010}}</ref> He continues to report on location for the Asian tsunami in Indonesia, [[International AIDS Conference]] in Vienna, and [[UN General Assembly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cntv.cn/reporter/james/index.shtml |title=James Chau, UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador for China \u2013 CCTV Host and Reporter |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[Millennium Development Goals]] Summit in New York.<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/>\n\nHe writes a newspaper column for the state-run tabloid ''[[Global Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/commentary/2010-09/577798_2.html |title=Aids won't wait for the recession to finish \u2013 GlobalTimes |publisher=Opinion.globaltimes.cn |date=27 September 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720164045/http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/commentary/2010-09/577798_2.html |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/foreign-view/2010-08/568525.html |title=Manila's botched bus rescue leaves a bad taste behind |work=Global Times |date=30 August 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720164022/http://opinion.globaltimes.cn/foreign-view/2010-08/568525.html |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador ==\nChau has been described as one of China's leading AIDS activists.<ref name=\"unaids.org.cn\">http://unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2009121808551558.pdf</ref><ref>http://unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2009111213035034.pdf</ref> He came under the early mentorship of Belgian scientist [[Peter Piot]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shenzhen.urbanatomy.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=302:secrets-a-lies-cctvs-james-chau&catid=144:features&Itemid=12 |title=that's PRD &#124; Listings, Events, Reviews, Jobs |publisher=Shenzhen.urbanatomy.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> who co-discovered the [[Ebola]] virus, and has traveled on health missions to India, Norway, Indonesia, and the United States.<ref name=\"unaids.org\"/> In August 2009, the United Nations announced his appointment as its first UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador on the Chinese Mainland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cctv.com/english/special/excl/20090814/110009.shtml |title=CCTV news anchor James Chau nominated \"UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador\" CCTV-International |publisher=Cctv.com |date=14 August 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> joining [[Naomi Watts]], [[Michael Ballack]] and [[Princess Stephanie of Monaco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/default.asp |title=Partnerships Department |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In April 2010, his first show as presenter of the new ''China 24'' program was headlined by China's lifting of the HIV-related travel ban,.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uaat-XhJoNw |title=James Chau Reports... China Lifts HIV Travel Ban |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassador, he has been featured in ''[[GQ]]'' and ''[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]]'',<ref name=\"unaids.org.cn\"/> and partners with leading Chinese internet portal, [[Sohu.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gongyi.sohu.com/20091128/n268541563.shtml |title=\u641c\u72d0\u4e3e\u529e\u827e\u6ecb\u75c5\u65e5\u4e3b\u9898\u6d3b\u52a8 \u5173\u6ce8\u53d7\u827e\u6ecb\u5f71\u54cd\u5b69\u5b50-\u516c\u76ca\u9891\u9053 |publisher=Gongyi.sohu.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> In 2008, he was named to the inaugural Young Leaders Summit at the [[Google]] headquarters,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/youngleaderssummit |title=Our2031 \u2013 Blog |publisher=Aids2031 |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724230327/http://www.aids2031.org/youngleaderssummit |archive-date=24 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and to the second edition hosted in Oslo by [[Crown Princess Mette-Marit of Norway]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/2009%20young%20leaders%20summit%20meeting%20report.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723171007/http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/2009%20young%20leaders%20summit%20meeting%20report.pdf |archive-date=23 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Chau chaired the closing session of the 2009 International Congress on AIDS in Asia and the Pacific in Bali, and hosted the opening televised town hall event of the 2010 International AIDS Conference in Vienna<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/KnowledgeCentre/Resources/FeatureStories/archive/2010/20100715_TownHall.asp |title=Join UNAIDS and IAS at Town Hall on reshaping the future of AIDS |publisher=Unaids.org |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> with singer and activist [[Annie Lennox]], UNAIDS Executive Director [[Michel Sidib\u00e9]], U.S. Congresswoman [[Barbara Lee]], and South African Deputy President [[Kgalema Motlanthe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2010-08/03/content_132698.htm?div=-1 |title=\u4e16\u754c\u827e\u6ecb\u75c5\u5927\u4f1a\u65b0\u8fdb\u5c55 -\u5065\u5eb7\u516c\u793e\u00b7\u5173\u6ce8-\u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7535\u5b50\u62a5 |publisher=Epaper.bjnews.com.cn |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalhealth.kff.org/AIDS2010/July-18/Towards-a-Paradigm-Shift-in-HIV-Treatment.aspx |title=Towards a Paradigm Shift in HIV Treatment and Prevention \u2013 Kaiser Global Health |publisher=Globalhealth.kff.org |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> At the same conference, he moderated the innovative financing debate between [[The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis and Malaria|Global Fund]] chief [[Michel Kazatchkine]] and former French Foreign Minister [[Philippe Douste-Blazy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalhealth.kff.org/AIDS2010/July-21/Funding-Global-Health.aspx |title=Funding Global Health: Can Innovative Mechanisms Save the Day? |publisher=Kaiser Global Health |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nChau is a member of aids2031<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/asian_economies_in_rapid_transition_hiv_now_and_through_2031%5B2%5D.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=7 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723171054/http://www.aids2031.org/pdfs/asian_economies_in_rapid_transition_hiv_now_and_through_2031%5B2%5D.pdf |archive-date=23 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Fashion Against AIDS|Designers Against AIDS]].\n\n== Interviews ==\nHe sat down with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe during the 2010 UN General Assembly,<ref name=\"english.cntv.cn\"/> and at the same event with United Nations Secretary General Ban Ki-moon,<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> Indian Foreign Secretary [[Nirupama Rao]],<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> Polish Foreign Minister [[Rados\u0142aw Sikorski]],<ref name=\"James Chau CCTV UN Millennium summit\"/> and South African Health Minister [[Aaron Motsoaledi]]. His other interview guests are Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Tun Razak]], Indonesian Trade Minister [[Mari Pangestu]], former [[King Constantine II of Greece]], [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]], former Botswanan President [[Festus Mogae]],<ref>http://www.unaids.org.cn/uploadFiles/2010081913251993.doc</ref> UNAIDS Executive Director [[Michel Sidib\u00e9]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-vq0YxTj6ts |title=James Chau Interviews... UN Under Secretary-General Michel Sidib\u00e9 |publisher=YouTube |date=30 September 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eVURMqeCvEc |title=James Chau Live... 2010 International AIDS Conference |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> U.S. Assistant Secretary for Health [[Howard Koh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cSAokwXeAXo |title=James Chau Interviews... U.S. Assistant Secretary for Health Howard Koh |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and First Lady of Georgia [[Sandra Roelofs|Sandra Saakashvili]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bm51g5TIECc |title=James Chau Interviews... First Lady of Georgia Sandra Saakashvili |publisher=YouTube |date=18 July 2010 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> From the arts, he profiled Freedom Towers architect [[Daniel Libeskind]], and in fashion, [[Jimmy Choo]], [[Vivienne Tam]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.james-chau.com/podcast/ |title=Podcast |publisher=James Chau |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and Jason Wu. His interview with Chinese military singer [[Peng Liyuan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gJKSOsMqKvc |title=James Chau Interviews... Chinese military general Peng Liyuan |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> was a rare television exclusive, and he has also spoken on camera to [[Crown Prince Haakon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rir705KKi3s |title=HRH Haakon and James Chau on Dignity and Respect \u2013 HIV/AIDS (Part 1) |publisher=YouTube |date=24 June 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> and [[Crown Princess Mette-Marit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0g3gAJ3geRU |title=HRH Mette-Marit and James Chau (Part 3) |publisher=YouTube |date=25 June 2009 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> of Norway, and French virologist [[Fran\u00e7oise Barr\u00e9-Sinoussi]],<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> whose co-discovery of HIV won her the Nobel Prize in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2008/press.html |title=The 2008 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine \u2013 Press Release |publisher=Nobelprize.org |date=6 October 2008 |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Other ==\nHe is a [[Freeman of the City of London]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tieba.baidu.com/f?kz=87336474 |title=Guild of Scholars of the City of London_\u5468\u5efa\u6210\u5427_\u8d34\u5427 |publisher=Tieba.baidu.com |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref> a [[National Press Foundation]] Fellow.,<ref>{{cite web |last=Meyers |first=Bob |url=http://nationalpress.org/blogs/aids/category/j2j/ |title=J2J &#124; NPF Helpdesk &#124; National Press Foundation |publisher=Nationalpress.org |accessdate=25 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229235509/http://nationalpress.org/blogs/aids/category/j2j/ |archive-date=29 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a representative of the [[British Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org/goingglobal-gg4-speakers-a-z.htm |title=A to Z \u2013 Session speakers- Going Global 4 |publisher=British Council |accessdate=25 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.james-chau.com Official website]\n* [http://www.unaids.org/en/Partnerships/Advocacy+partners/SpecRep/default.asp UNAIDS Goodwill Ambassadors]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chau, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chinese columnists]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:China Central Television]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Chau"}
{"title_page": "Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|L\u00f3pez|Caro}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro\n| image = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro.jpg\n| caption = Caro in a press conference as [[Oman national football team|Oman]] manager in 2016\n| fullname = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|3|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lebrija]], Spain\n| height = \n| position = \n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[UB Lebrijana|Lebrijana]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Real Betis|Betis]]\n| years1 = | clubs1 = | caps1 = | goals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1992\u20131993 | managerclubs1 = [[UB Lebrijana|Lebrijana]]\n| manageryears2 = 1993\u20131995 | managerclubs2 = Lebrija\n| manageryears3 = 1995\u20131997 | managerclubs3 = [[UD Los Palacios|Los Palacios]]\n| manageryears4 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs4 = [[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]]\n| manageryears5 = 1998\u20131999 | managerclubs5 = [[UD Melilla|Melilla]]\n| manageryears6 = 1999\u20132001 | managerclubs6 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] \n| manageryears7 = 2000 | managerclubs7 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| manageryears8 = 2001\u20132005 | managerclubs8 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]]\n| manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| manageryears10 = 2006 | managerclubs10 = [[Racing de Santander|Racing Santander]]\n| manageryears11 = 2006\u20132007 | managerclubs11 = [[Levante UD|Levante]]\n| manageryears12 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs12 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n| manageryears13 = 2008\u20132010 | managerclubs13 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| manageryears14 = 2010 | managerclubs14 = [[FC Vaslui|Vaslui]]\n| manageryears15 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs15 = [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]\n| manageryears16 = 2016 | managerclubs16 = [[Oman national football team|Oman]]\n| manageryears17 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs17 = [[Dalian Yifang F.C.|Dalian Yifang]]\n| manageryears18 = 2018\u20132019 | managerclubs18 = [[Shenzhen F.C.|Shenzhen]]\n}}\n'''Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro''' ({{IPA-es|xwanra\u02c8mon \u02c8lope\u03b8 \u02c8ka\u027eo}}; born 23 March 1963) is a Spanish [[Association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nHe managed [[Real Madrid]] and [[Levante UD|Levante]] in [[La Liga]], as well as [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] and [[Real Madrid Castilla]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]. After a spell in charge of [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21]] he moved abroad, managing the national sides of [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] and [[Oman national football team|Oman]], and winning promotion from [[China League One]] with two clubs.\n\n==Football career==\n===Early career / Real Madrid===\nBorn in [[Lebrija]], [[Province of Seville]], [[Andalusia]], L\u00f3pez Caro began working as coach before his 30th birthday, with clubs in his city of birth. His first job at the professional level arrived in the [[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1998\u201399 season]], as he led [[UD Melilla]] to the first position in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], albeit without promotion in [[1999 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|the playoffs]]. He then became manager of [[RCD Mallorca B]], and officially coached the [[RCD Mallorca|first team]] in the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]] against Romania's [[CSM Ceahl\u0103ul Piatra Neam\u021b]] in July 2000 ([[2000 UEFA Intertoto Cup|4\u20133 aggregate loss]]); the reserves contested this fixture as [[Luis Aragon\u00e9s]]' side had not yet commenced pre-season.<ref>{{cite news |title=En Mallorca no olvidan al t\u00e9cnico |trans-title=In Mallorca they don't forget the manager|url=https://as.com/futbol/2006/02/26/mas_futbol/1140938817_850215.html |accessdate=4 January 2020 |work=[[Diario AS]] |date=26 February 2006 |language=Spanish}}</ref> \n\nLop\u00e9z Caro signed with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the summer of 2001, being in charge of [[Real Madrid Castilla|the reserve team]] also in the third level and achieving promotion to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] in [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2005]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2005/06/27/mas_futbol/1119853615_850215.html|title=El Madrid B toca el cielo|trans-title=Madrid B knock on heaven's door|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=Fornieles|first=Raquel|language=Spanish|date=27 June 2005|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> He was promoted to the main squad in December of that year following the sacking of [[Vanderlei Luxemburgo]], and his first game was a 1\u20132 away loss against [[Olympiacos F.C.]] for [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|the campaign]]'s [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/juventud-suficiente/20051207dasdaiftb_7/Tes|title=La juventud no es suficiente|trans-title=Youth is not enough|newspaper=Diario AS|last=Trueba|first=Juanma|language=Spanish|date=7 December 2005|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Levante / Celta / Spain U21===\nAfter leaving the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] in June 2006, L\u00f3pez Caro was appointed at fellow top-flight club [[Racing de Santander]] for a salary of \u20ac650,000 that would rise to \u20ac900,000 should the team avoid relegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/PUB/2006/06/03/EMD20060603038MDP.pdf|title=Caro: \"Voy a luchar a muerte\"|trans-title=Caro: \"I will fight to the death\"|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=L\u00e1varo|first=E.|language=Spanish|date=3 June 2006|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> However, a month later and without leading the [[Cantabria]]ns in a competitive match, he moved to [[Levante UD]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eldia.es/2006-07-06/jornada/jornada49.htm|title=L\u00f3pez Caro no llegar\u00e1 a entrenar al Racing y se incorpora al Levante|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro will not coach Racing and joins Levante|newspaper=[[El D\u00eda (Canary Islands)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=6 July 2006|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The following January, days after a 3\u20130 loss at city rivals [[Valencia CF]], he was dismissed and [[Abel Resino]] appointed in his place.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gim\u00e9nez |first1=Jordi |title=El Levante destituye a L\u00f3pez Caro y presenta a Abel como nuevo t\u00e9cnico|trans-title=Levante dismiss L\u00f3pez Caro and present Abel as new manager |url=https://www.lasprovincias.es/valencia/prensa/20070116/deportes/levante-destituye-lopez-caro_20070116.html |accessdate=4 January 2020 |work=[[Las Provincias]] |date=16 January 2007 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diarioinformacion.com/deportes/1925/levante-destituye-lopez-caro-ficha-abel-resino-sustituirle/592233.html|title=El Levante destituye a L\u00f3pez Caro y ficha a Abel Resino para sustituirle|trans-title=Levante fire L\u00f3pez Caro and sign Abel Resino as his replacement|newspaper=Diario Informaci\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nL\u00f3pez Caro returned to the second tier in October 2007, succeeding [[Hristo Stoichkov]] at 11th-placed [[RC Celta de Vigo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertaddigital.com/deportes/lopez-caro-nuevo-entrenador-del-celta-tras-la-marcha-de-stoichkov-1276314999/|title=L\u00f3pez Caro, nuevo entrenador del Celta tras la marcha de Stoichkov|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, new Celta manager after departure of Stoichkov|publisher=Libertad Digital|language=Spanish|date=8 October 2007|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> The following March, he too was ousted, with the team now in eighth but nine points off the promotion places.<ref>{{cite news |title=L\u00f3pez Caro destituido como t\u00e9cnico del Celta de Vigo|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro dismissed as manager of Celta de Vigo |url=https://www.laopiniondezamora.es/deportes/2008/03/11/lopez-caro-destituido-tecnico-celta-vigo/262205.html |accessdate=4 January 2020 |work=La Opini\u00f3n de Zamora |date=11 March 2008 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, L\u00f3pez Caro had his first international job, being placed in charge of [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain under-21]] succeeding [[I\u00f1aki S\u00e1ez]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Luis Enrique, nuevo entrenador del Barcelona B |trans-title=Luis Enrique, new manager of Barcelona B|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2008/05/26/actualidad/1211786516_850215.html |accessdate=4 January 2020 |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=26 May 2008 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He qualified the team for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2009 UEFA European Championship]] in Sweden,<ref>{{cite news |title=La selecci\u00f3n sub'21 cierra la fase de clasificaci\u00f3n con \u00e9xito|trans-title=Under-21 team successfully complete qualification phase |url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2008/09/09/futbol/1220991166.html |accessdate=4 January 2020 |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=9 September 2008 |language=Spanish}}</ref> where they were edged in the group stage by [[England national under-21 football team|England]] and [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]].\n\n===Vaslui / Middle East===\nIn June 2010, L\u00f3pez Caro moved abroad for the first time to [[Liga I]]'s [[FC Vaslui]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=1497901.html|title=L\u00f3pez Caro accepts Vaslui baton|publisher=UEFA|date=14 June 2010|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> on a three-year deal for a total \u20ac3.5 million salary subject to bonuses, therefore becoming the best paid coach in the competition's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosport.ro/fotbal-intern/liga-1/cel-mai-scump-antrenor-din-istoria-ligii-i-a-ajuns-la-vaslui-6423196|title=Cel mai scump antrenor din istoria Ligii I a ajuns la Vaslui|trans-title=Best paid coach in history of Liga I joins Vaslui|publisher=[[ProSport]]|language=Romanian|date=15 June 2010|accessdate=3 August 2010}}</ref> He was relieved of his duties in October, after enduring a rocky spell in Romania.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/09/01/futbol/futbol_internacional/espanoles_mundo/1283323096.html|title=La incre\u00edble pesadilla de L\u00f3pez Caro en Ruman\u00eda|trans-title=The incredible nightmare of L\u00f3pez Caro in Romania|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Niculescu|first=Andrei|language=Spanish|date=1 September 2010|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2010/10/09/futbol/1286620536.html|title=L\u00f3pez Caro, destituido como t\u00e9cnico del Vaslui|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, fired as Vaslui coach|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=9 October 2010|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, L\u00f3pez Caro succeeded [[Frank Rijkaard]] as manager of the [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia national team]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia appoint Lopez Caro |url=https://www.football-espana.net/27641/saudi-arabia-appoint-lopez-caro |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a |date=17 January 2013}}</ref> After a disappointing showing in the [[Gulf Cup]] in the run-up to the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup]], he was dismissed in December 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia sack coach Lopez Caro a month before Asian Cup |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/soccer-asia-saudi/saudi-arabia-sack-coach-lopez-caro-a-month-before-asian-cup-idINKCN0JK01B20141206 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=6 December 2014}}</ref> He remained in the Middle East and was hired for the same job by [[Oman national football team|Oman]] in January 2016,<ref>{{cite news |title=Oman sets three targets for new coach Lopez Caro |url=https://timesofoman.com/article/75505 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |work=Times of Oman |date=15 January 2016}}</ref> and left by mutual accord at the end of his one-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=OFA thanks coach Lopez Caro for tenure |url=http://www.ofa.om/ofa-thanks-coach-lopez-caro-tenure |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=Oman Football Association |date=29 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===China===\nRemaining in Asia, L\u00f3pez Caro was hired by [[Dalian Yifang F.C.]] of [[China League One]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=L\u00f3pez Caro entrenar\u00e1 al Dalian Yifang de la segunda divisi\u00f3n china |trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro will manage Dalian Yifang of the Chinese second division|url=https://www.wradio.com.co/noticias/deportes/lopez-caro-entrenara-al-dalian-yifang-de-la-segunda-division-china/20161129/nota/3317978.aspx |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=W Radio |date=30 November 2016 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In his [[2017 China League One|only season]], he won promotion to the [[Chinese Super League]] with a record points tally and a game to spare.<ref name=dalian>{{cite news |last1=Sainz de Vicu\u00f1a |first1=Mikel |title=L\u00f3pez Caro, un campe\u00f3n de r\u00e9cord|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, a record-breaking champion |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/liga-china/2017/10/21/59eb23f1268e3e89338b45fb.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Marca |date=21 October 2017 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, L\u00f3pez Caro was appointed at [[Shenzhen F.C.]] again in the second division and won promotion, this time as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |title=El espa\u00f1ol L\u00f3pez Caro, nuevo entrenador del Shenzhen en la 2\u00aa divisi\u00f3n china|trans-title=Spaniard L\u00f3pez Caro, new manager of Shenzhen in the Chinese 2nd division |url=https://www.diariodesevilla.es/deportes/Lopez-Caro-entrenador-Shenzhen-division_0_1235877035.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Diario de Sevilla |date=13 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He was dismissed at the end of July 2019 with the side second from bottom in a 12-game winless run, and succeeded by [[Roberto Donadoni]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Donadoni replaces Lopez Caro at Shenzhen helm |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-china/donadoni-replaces-lopez-caro-at-shenzhen-helm-idUKKCN1UP07O |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|28 July 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway coach|juan-ramon-lopez-caro/136263}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\t\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=\"2\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\t\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[UD Los Palacios|Los Palacios]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 1995\n|align=left|30 June 1997\n{{WDL|80|32|20|28}}\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Nacionales/1995-96/9596-3-10.htm|title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Grupo 10) 1995\u201396|trans-title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Group 10) 1995\u201396|publisher=Futbolme|language=Spanish|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Nacionales/1996-97/9697-3-10.htm|title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Grupo 10) 1996\u201397|trans-title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Group 10) 1996\u201397|publisher=Futbolme|language=Spanish|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 1997\n|align=left|30 June 1998\n{{WDL|38|30|7|1}}\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Regionales/Andalucia/Sevilla/1997-98/9798-p.htm|title=Regional Preferente Sevillana 1997\u201398|trans-title=Regional Preferente Sevillana 1997\u201398|publisher=Futbolme|language=Spanish|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[UD Melilla|Melilla]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 1998\n|align=left|30 June 1999\n{{WDL|44|21|11|12}}\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=1998-99|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 1999\n|align=left|30 June 2001\n{{WDL|76|32|29|15}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=1999-00|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?cat=-&temp=2000-01&equip=69&rival=-|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|30 June 2000\n|align=left|9 July 2000\n{{WDL|2|1|0|1}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?cat=-&temp=2000-01&equip=24&rival=-|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left| [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 2001\n|align=left|4 December 2005\n{{WDL|183|97|45|41}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2001-02|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2002-03|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2003-04|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2004-05|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?cat=-&temp=2005-06&equip=61&rival=-|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|4 December 2005\n|align=left|3 June 2006\n{{WDL|33|17|10|6}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?cat=-&temp=2005-06&equip=2&rival=-|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left| [[Racing de Santander|Racing Santander]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|3 June 2006\n|align=left|6 July 2006\n{{WDL|0|0|0|0}}\n|\n|-\n|align=left|[[Levante UD|Levante]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|6 July 2006\n|align=left|15 January 2007\n{{WDL|20|5|6|9}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2006-07|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|8 October 2007\n|align=left|11 March 2008\n{{WDL|21|7|8|6}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?temp=2007-08|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 2008\n|align=left|14 June 2010\n{{WDL|17|9|3|5}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l7370.html?cat=S21|title=L\u00f3pez Caro: Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Vaslui|Vaslui]]\n|{{flagicon|Romania}}\n|align=left|14 June 2010\n|align=left|9 October 2010\n{{WDL|13|4|5|4}}\n|\n|-\n|align=left| [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]\n|{{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}}\n|align=left|10 January 2013\n|align=left|15 December 2014\n{{WDL|22|9|5|8}}\n|\n|-\n|align=left|[[Oman national football team|Oman]]\n|{{flagicon|Oman}}\n|align=left|14 January 2016\n|align=left|29 November 2016\n{{WDL|8|3|2|3}}\n|\n|-\n|align=left| [[Dalian Yifang F.C.|Dalian Yifang]]\n|{{flagicon|China}}\n|align=left|29 November 2016\n|align=left|26 December 2017\n{{WDL|32|19|8|5}}\n|\n|-\n|align=left| [[Shenzhen F.C.|Shenzhen]]\n|{{flagicon|China}}\n|align=left|11 April 2018\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|46|17|11|18}}\n|\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|635|303|170|162}}\t\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Melilla'''\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]: [[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1998\u201399]]\n\n'''Real Madrid B'''\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]: [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''Dalian Yifang'''\n*[[China League One]]: [[2017 China League One|2017]]<ref name=dalian/>\n\n===International===\n'''Saudi Arabia'''\n*[[Gulf Cup of Nations]]: Runner-up [[2014 Gulf Cup of Nations|2014]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[China League One]]: Best Coach [[2017 China League One|2017]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol manager|7370}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro \u2013 Managerial positions\n|list1 =\n{{Real Madrid Castilla managers}}\n{{Real Madrid C.F. managers}}\n{{Racing de Santander managers}}\n{{Levante UD managers}}\n{{Celta de Vigo managers}}\n{{FC Vaslui managers}}\n{{Dalian Yifang F.C. managers}}\n{{Shenzhen F.C. managers}}\n{{Spain national under-21 football team managers}}\n{{Saudi Arabia national football team managers}}\n{{Oman national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{China League One Coach of the Season}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez Caro, Juan Ramon}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lebrija]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:UD Melilla managers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid Castilla managers]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF managers]]\n[[Category:Racing de Santander managers]]\n[[Category:Levante UD managers]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo managers]]\n[[Category:FC Vaslui managers]]\n[[Category:Spain national under-21 football team managers]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Oman national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Oman]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in China]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Oman]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|L\u00f3pez|Caro}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro\n| image = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro.jpg\n| caption = Caro in a press conference as [[Oman national football team|Oman]] manager in 2016\n| fullname = Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1963|3|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lebrija]], Spain\n| height = \n| position = \n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[UB Lebrijana|Lebrijana]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Real Betis|Betis]]\n| years1 = | clubs1 = | caps1 = | goals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1992\u20131993 | managerclubs1 = [[UB Lebrijana|Lebrijana]]\n| manageryears2 = 1993\u20131995 | managerclubs2 = Lebrija\n| manageryears3 = 1995\u20131997 | managerclubs3 = [[UD Los Palacios|Los Palacios]]\n| manageryears4 = 1997\u20131998 | managerclubs4 = [[Dos Hermanas CF|Dos Hermanas]]\n| manageryears5 = 1998\u20131999 | managerclubs5 = [[UD Melilla|Melilla]]\n| manageryears6 = 1999\u20132001 | managerclubs6 = [[RCD Mallorca B|Mallorca B]] \n| manageryears7 = 2000 | managerclubs7 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| manageryears8 = 2001\u20132005 | managerclubs8 = [[Real Madrid Castilla|Real Madrid B]]\n| manageryears9 = 2005\u20132006 | managerclubs9 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]\n| manageryears10 = 2006 | managerclubs10 = [[Racing de Santander|Racing Santander]]\n| manageryears11 = 2006\u20132007 | managerclubs11 = [[Levante UD|Levante]]\n| manageryears12 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs12 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n| manageryears13 = 2008\u20132010 | managerclubs13 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]]\n| manageryears14 = 2010 | managerclubs14 = [[FC Vaslui|Vaslui]]\n| manageryears15 = 2013\u20132014 | managerclubs15 = [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]\n| manageryears16 = 2016 | managerclubs16 = [[Oman national football team|Oman]]\n| manageryears17 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs17 = [[Dalian Yifang F.C.|Dalian Yifang]]\n| manageryears18 = 2018\u20132019 | managerclubs18 = [[Shenzhen F.C.|Shenzhen]]\n}}\n'''Juan Ram\u00f3n L\u00f3pez Caro''' ({{IPA-es|xwanra\u02c8mon \u02c8lope\u03b8 \u02c8ka\u027eo}}; born 23 March 1963) is a Spanish [[Association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\n==Football career==\nBorn in [[Lebrija]], [[Province of Seville]], [[Andalusia]], L\u00f3pez Caro began working as coach before his 30th birthday, with clubs in his city of birth. His first job at the professional level arrived in the [[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1998\u201399 season]], as he led [[UD Melilla]] to the first position in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], albeit without promotion in [[1999 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|the playoffs]].\n\nLop\u00e9z Caro signed with [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in the summer of 2001, from [[RCD Mallorca B]], being in charge of [[Real Madrid Castilla|the reserve team]] also in the third level and achieving promotion to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] in [[2004\u201305 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2005]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2005/06/27/mas_futbol/1119853615_850215.html|title=El Madrid B toca el cielo|trans-title=Madrid B knock on heaven's door|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=Fornieles|first=Raquel|language=Spanish|date=27 June 2005|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> He was promoted to the main squad in December of that year following the sacking of [[Vanderlei Luxemburgo]], and his first game was a 1\u20132 away loss against [[Olympiacos F.C.]] for [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|the campaign]]'s [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.as.com/futbol/articulo/juventud-suficiente/20051207dasdaiftb_7/Tes|title=La juventud no es suficiente|trans-title=Youth is not enough|newspaper=Diario AS|last=Trueba|first=Juanma|language=Spanish|date=7 December 2005|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the following years, L\u00f3pez Caro worked with [[Racing de Santander]] \u2013 he did not actually appear in any competitive matches<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca-paginas.mundodeportivo.com/EMD02/PUB/2006/06/03/EMD20060603038MDP.pdf|title=Caro: \"Voy a luchar a muerte\"|trans-title=Caro: \"I will fight to the death\"|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last=L\u00e1varo|first=E.|language=Spanish|date=3 June 2006|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\u2013 [[Levante UD]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eldia.es/2006-07-06/jornada/jornada49.htm|title=L\u00f3pez Caro no llegar\u00e1 a entrenar al Racing y se incorpora al Levante|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro will not coach Racing and joins Levante|newspaper=[[El D\u00eda (Canary Islands)|El D\u00eda]]|language=Spanish|date=6 July 2006|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> and [[RC Celta de Vigo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertaddigital.com/deportes/lopez-caro-nuevo-entrenador-del-celta-tras-la-marcha-de-stoichkov-1276314999/|title=L\u00f3pez Caro, nuevo entrenador del Celta tras la marcha de Stoichkov|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, new Celta manager after departure of Stoichkov|publisher=Libertad Digital|language=Spanish|date=8 October 2007|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> being at the helm of the second side in [[La Liga]] for less than five months.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diarioinformacion.com/deportes/1925/levante-destituye-lopez-caro-ficha-abel-resino-sustituirle/592233.html|title=El Levante destituye a L\u00f3pez Caro y ficha a Abel Resino para sustituirle|trans-title=Levante fire L\u00f3pez Caro and sign Abel Resino as his replacement|newspaper=Diario Informaci\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=16 January 2007|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref> In June 2010, after two years with the [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spanish under-21s]], he moved abroad, joining [[Liga I]]'s [[FC Vaslui]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=1497901.html|title=L\u00f3pez Caro accepts Vaslui baton|publisher=UEFA|date=14 June 2010|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> and becoming the best paid coach in the competition's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosport.ro/fotbal-intern/liga-1/cel-mai-scump-antrenor-din-istoria-ligii-i-a-ajuns-la-vaslui-6423196|title=Cel mai scump antrenor din istoria Ligii I a ajuns la Vaslui|trans-title=Best paid coach in history of Liga I joins Vaslui|publisher=[[ProSport]]|language=Romanian|date=15 June 2010|accessdate=3 August 2010}}</ref> He was relieved of his duties in October, after enduring a rocky spell in [[Romania]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/09/01/futbol/futbol_internacional/espanoles_mundo/1283323096.html|title=La incre\u00edble pesadilla de L\u00f3pez Caro en Ruman\u00eda|trans-title=The incredible nightmare of L\u00f3pez Caro in Romania|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Niculescu|first=Andrei|language=Spanish|date=1 September 2010|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2010/10/09/futbol/1286620536.html|title=L\u00f3pez Caro, destituido como t\u00e9cnico del Vaslui|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, fired as Vaslui coach|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|date=9 October 2010|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, L\u00f3pez Caro succeeded [[Frank Rijkaard]] as manager of the [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia national team]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia appoint Lopez Caro |url=https://www.football-espana.net/27641/saudi-arabia-appoint-lopez-caro |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a |date=17 January 2013}}</ref> After a disappointing showing in the [[Gulf Cup]] in the run-up to the [[2015 AFC Asian Cup]], he was dismissed in December 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Saudi Arabia sack coach Lopez Caro a month before Asian Cup |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/soccer-asia-saudi/saudi-arabia-sack-coach-lopez-caro-a-month-before-asian-cup-idINKCN0JK01B20141206 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=6 December 2014}}</ref> He remained in the Middle East and was hired for the same job by [[Oman national football team|Oman]] in January 2016,<ref>{{cite news |title=Oman sets three targets for new coach Lopez Caro |url=https://timesofoman.com/article/75505 |accessdate=2 October 2019 |work=Times of Oman |date=15 January 2016}}</ref> and left by mutual accord at the end of his one-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=OFA thanks coach Lopez Caro for tenure |url=http://www.ofa.om/ofa-thanks-coach-lopez-caro-tenure |accessdate=2 October 2019 |publisher=Oman Football Association |date=29 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nRemaining in Asia, L\u00f3pez Caro was hired by [[Dalian Yifang F.C.]] of [[China League One]] in November 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=L\u00f3pez Caro entrenar\u00e1 al Dalian Yifang de la segunda divisi\u00f3n china |trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro will manage Dalian Yifang of the Chinese second division|url=https://www.wradio.com.co/noticias/deportes/lopez-caro-entrenara-al-dalian-yifang-de-la-segunda-division-china/20161129/nota/3317978.aspx |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=W Radio |date=30 November 2016 |language=Spanish}}</ref> In his [[2017 China League One|only season]], he won promotion to the [[Chinese Super League]] with a record points tally and a game to spare.<ref name=dalian>{{cite news |last1=Sainz de Vicu\u00f1a |first1=Mikel |title=L\u00f3pez Caro, un campe\u00f3n de r\u00e9cord|trans-title=L\u00f3pez Caro, a record-breaking champion |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/liga-china/2017/10/21/59eb23f1268e3e89338b45fb.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Marca |date=21 October 2017 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, L\u00f3pez Caro was appointed at [[Shenzhen F.C.]] again in the second division and won promotion, this time as runners-up.<ref>{{cite news |title=El espa\u00f1ol L\u00f3pez Caro, nuevo entrenador del Shenzhen en la 2\u00aa divisi\u00f3n china|trans-title=Spaniard L\u00f3pez Caro, new manager of Shenzhen in the Chinese 2nd division |url=https://www.diariodesevilla.es/deportes/Lopez-Caro-entrenador-Shenzhen-division_0_1235877035.html |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Diario de Sevilla |date=13 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref> He was dismissed at the end of July 2019 with the side second from bottom in a 12-game winless run, and succeeded by [[Roberto Donadoni]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Donadoni replaces Lopez Caro at Shenzhen helm |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-china/donadoni-replaces-lopez-caro-at-shenzhen-helm-idUKKCN1UP07O |accessdate=11 November 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|28 July 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway coach|juan-ramon-lopez-caro/136263}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\t\t\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n!rowspan=\"2\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\t\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[UD Los Palacios|Los Palacios]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n|align=left|1 July 1995\n|align=left|30 June 1997\n{{WDL|80|32|20|28}}\t\n|<ref>