{"title_page": "Carterton railway station (England)", "text_new": "{{For|the station in New Zealand|Carterton railway station}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name      = Carterton\n| image_name = Carterton 1 62573 1.jpg\n| caption   = January 1962\n| locale    = [[Carterton, Oxfordshire|Carterton]]\n| borough   = [[West Oxfordshire]]\n| original  = [[Great Western Railway]] \n| pregroup  = <!-- intentionally blank -->\n| postgroup = Great Western Railway\n| platforms = 2\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.74104|-1.58766|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref   = SP286048\n| years     = 2 October 1944\n| events    = Station opens\n| years1    = 18 June 1962\n| events1   = Station Closes \n}}\n{{Oxford, Witney and Fairford Railway|collapse=yes}}\n\n'''Carterton railway station''' was a [[railway station]] just north of the village of [[Black Bourton]] on the [[Oxford, Witney and Fairford Railway]] between {{stnlnk|Oxford}} and {{stnlnk|Fairford}}.{{sfnp|Conolly|1976|loc=p. 10, section E5}} The station had two stone-built platforms, a passing loop, and a concrete station building. \n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Carterton halt site geograph-3843837-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Station site in 1990]]\n\nBuilt next to the [[Carterton, Oxfordshire|Carterton]] to [[Black Bourton]] road less than two miles from [[Brize Norton and Bampton railway station]], the station was opened on 2 October 1944,{{sfnp|Butt|1995|p=55}}{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=116}} to serve [[RAF Brize Norton]] which had opened in August 1937.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=68, 97}}{{sfnp|Simpson|1997|p=180}}{{sfnp|Waters|1986|p=27}} It had initially been considered to name the station \"Black Bourton\".{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 75}}\n\nConstruction of the station had begun in May 1944 when a [[rail siding|siding]] was laid on the Down side which, three months later, was adapted as a [[passing loop]] opened on 10 August, {{convert|18|chain|m}} in length and fully signalled for passenger services.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=68-69}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 73}} The station had platforms on the Up and Down lines; an austere [[War Department (United Kingdom)|War Department]]-type structure resembling an [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] hut, stood on the Up side.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=69, 97}} The front of the building was sheltered by a makeshift asbestos canopy and a traditional timber [[signal box]] stood just beyond the end of the Up platform.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=96-97}} A very basic corrugated iron shelter was provided on the Down platform.{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 76}} No goods facilities were provided as Brize Norton and Bampton station lay within close proximity {{convert|1|mi|32|chain|km}} to the east,{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=69, 97}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 77}} although agricultural produce from smallholdings in Carterton were often dispatched by passenger train.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=97}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 74}}\n\nThe position of the line in relation to the airfield meant that when its facilities were extended southwards, two essential [[taxiway]]s crossed the railway line necessitating wide [[level crossing]] gates to span the entire width.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=68}} After the war, the airfields continued to generate significant traffic until the early 1950s when Brize Norton became a [[United States Air Force|USAF]] base and traffic suddenly fell away.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=70}} By June 1958 there was only one daily freight service on the line: a morning working from Carterton to Oxford.{{sfnp|Simpson|1997|p=187}}\n\nThe station closed along with the East Gloucestershire Railway from Witney to Fairford on 18 June 1962.{{sfnp|Butt|1995|p=55}}{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=116}}{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=112}}{{sfnp|Clinker|1988|p=26}}\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Brize Norton and Bampton}}<br><small>Line and station closed|previous={{rws|Alvescot}}<br><small>Line and station closed|route=[[Great Western Railway]]<br><small>[[East Gloucestershire Railway]]<small><br><small>|col={{GWR colour}} }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Present day==\nThe line between Carterton and Brize Norton and Bampton has been severed as a result of the southward expansion of RAF Brize Norton.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=147}} The station building has survived, the only one to do so on the East Gloucestershire Railway, and was used for some time as a pig farm, then storage of farm machinery.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=147}}<ref name=\"Loader\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fairfordbranch.co.uk/Carterton.htm |title=Carterton |work=The Fairford Branch Line |publisher=Martin Loader |accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> It was reclad in timber in 1980 and is now used as stabling.<ref name=\"Loader\"/>\n\nThe station site may be identified by reference to the roadbridge which carries the Black Bourton road over the disused railway.{{sfnp|Waters|Doyle|1992|p=100}} The trackbed towards Fairford has become a rural track used by the local farmer.{{sfnp|Stretton|2006|p=90}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n*{{Clinker-Stations|year=1988}}\n*{{cite book |last=Conolly |first=W. Philip |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer |edition=5th |date=January 1976 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |id=EX/0176 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Jenkins|first1=Stanley C.|title=The Fairford Branch|origyear=1975|year=1985|publisher=Oakwood Press|id=LP86|location=Headington|isbn=0-853613-16-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Victor E. |last2=Smith |first2=Keith |last3=Lingard |first3=Richard |title=Branch Line to Fairford |date=April 1988 |publisher=Middleton Press |location=Midhurst |isbn=0-906520-52-5 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Quick-Stations}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Simpson|first1=Bill|title=A History of the Railways of Oxfordshire; Part 1: The North|year=1997|publisher=Lamplight Publications|location=Witney|isbn=978-1-89924-602-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Stretton|first1=John|title=British Railways Past and Present: Oxfordshire; A Second Selection|id=No. 55|year=2006|publisher=Past & Present Publishing|location=Kettering|isbn=978-1-85895-203-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Waters|first1=Laurence|last2=Doyle|first2=Tony|title=British Railways Past and Present: Oxfordshire|id=No. 15|year=1992|publisher=Silver Link Publishing|location=Wadenhoe|isbn=978-0-94797-187-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Waters|first1=Laurence|title=Rail Centres: Oxford|year=1986|publisher=Ian Allan|location=London|isbn=978-0-7110-1590-6|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fairfordbranch.co.uk/Carterton.htm  Photos and details about the station]\n*[http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#428,204,1 Station on a 1947 O.S. Map]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120201144206/http://www.d.m.howse.btinternet.co.uk/closure.html Archived page with post-closure details of stations]\n\n{{Closed stations Oxfordshire}}\n\n[[Category:Former Great Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1944]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1962]]\n[[Category:West Oxfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the station in New Zealand|Carterton Railway Station}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n| name      = Carterton\n| image_name = Carterton 1 62573 1.jpg\n| caption   = January 1962\n| locale    = [[Carterton, Oxfordshire|Carterton]]\n| borough   = [[West Oxfordshire]]\n| original  = [[Great Western Railway]] \n| pregroup  = <!-- intentionally blank -->\n| postgroup = Great Western Railway\n| platforms = 2\n| coordinates = {{coord|51.74104|-1.58766|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref   = SP286048\n| years     = 2 October 1944\n| events    = Station opens\n| years1    = 18 June 1962\n| events1   = Station Closes \n}}\n{{Oxford, Witney and Fairford Railway|collapse=yes}}\n\n'''Carterton railway station''' was a [[railway station]] just north of the village of [[Black Bourton]] on the [[Oxford, Witney and Fairford Railway]] between {{stnlnk|Oxford}} and {{stnlnk|Fairford}}.{{sfnp|Conolly|1976|loc=p. 10, section E5}} The station had two stone-built platforms, a passing loop, and a concrete station building. \n\n==History==\n\n[[File:Carterton halt site geograph-3843837-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|left|Station site in 1990]]\n\nBuilt next to the [[Carterton, Oxfordshire|Carterton]] to [[Black Bourton]] road less than two miles from [[Brize Norton and Bampton railway station]], the station was opened on 2 October 1944,{{sfnp|Butt|1995|p=55}}{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=116}} to serve [[RAF Brize Norton]] which had opened in August 1937.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=68, 97}}{{sfnp|Simpson|1997|p=180}}{{sfnp|Waters|1986|p=27}} It had initially been considered to name the station \"Black Bourton\".{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 75}}\n\nConstruction of the station had begun in May 1944 when a [[rail siding|siding]] was laid on the Down side which, three months later, was adapted as a [[passing loop]] opened on 10 August, {{convert|18|chain|m}} in length and fully signalled for passenger services.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=68-69}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 73}} The station had platforms on the Up and Down lines; an austere [[War Department (United Kingdom)|War Department]]-type structure resembling an [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] hut, stood on the Up side.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=69, 97}} The front of the building was sheltered by a makeshift asbestos canopy and a traditional timber [[signal box]] stood just beyond the end of the Up platform.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=96-97}} A very basic corrugated iron shelter was provided on the Down platform.{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 76}} No goods facilities were provided as Brize Norton and Bampton station lay within close proximity {{convert|1|mi|32|chain|km}} to the east,{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|pp=69, 97}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 77}} although agricultural produce from smallholdings in Carterton were often dispatched by passenger train.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=97}}{{sfnp|Mitchell|Smith|Lingard|1988|loc=fig. 74}}\n\nThe position of the line in relation to the airfield meant that when its facilities were extended southwards, two essential [[taxiway]]s crossed the railway line necessitating wide [[level crossing]] gates to span the entire width.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=68}} After the war, the airfields continued to generate significant traffic until the early 1950s when Brize Norton became a [[United States Air Force|USAF]] base and traffic suddenly fell away.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=70}} By June 1958 there was only one daily freight service on the line: a morning working from Carterton to Oxford.{{sfnp|Simpson|1997|p=187}}\n\nThe station closed along with the East Gloucestershire Railway from Witney to Fairford on 18 June 1962.{{sfnp|Butt|1995|p=55}}{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=116}}{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=112}}{{sfnp|Clinker|1988|p=26}}\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|next={{rws|Brize Norton and Bampton}}<br><small>Line and station closed|previous={{rws|Alvescot}}<br><small>Line and station closed|route=[[Great Western Railway]]<br><small>[[East Gloucestershire Railway]]<small><br><small>|col={{GWR colour}} }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Present day==\nThe line between Carterton and Brize Norton and Bampton has been severed as a result of the southward expansion of RAF Brize Norton.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=147}} The station building has survived, the only one to do so on the East Gloucestershire Railway, and was used for some time as a pig farm, then storage of farm machinery.{{sfnp|Jenkins|1985|p=147}}<ref name=\"Loader\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fairfordbranch.co.uk/Carterton.htm |title=Carterton |work=The Fairford Branch Line |publisher=Martin Loader |accessdate=4 July 2013}}</ref> It was reclad in timber in 1980 and is now used as stabling.<ref name=\"Loader\"/>\n\nThe station site may be identified by reference to the roadbridge which carries the Black Bourton road over the disused railway.{{sfnp|Waters|Doyle|1992|p=100}} The trackbed towards Fairford has become a rural track used by the local farmer.{{sfnp|Stretton|2006|p=90}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n*{{Clinker-Stations|year=1988}}\n*{{cite book |last=Conolly |first=W. Philip |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas and Gazetteer |edition=5th |date=January 1976 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |id=EX/0176 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Jenkins|first1=Stanley C.|title=The Fairford Branch|origyear=1975|year=1985|publisher=Oakwood Press|id=LP86|location=Headington|isbn=0-853613-16-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Victor E. |last2=Smith |first2=Keith |last3=Lingard |first3=Richard |title=Branch Line to Fairford |date=April 1988 |publisher=Middleton Press |location=Midhurst |isbn=0-906520-52-5 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Quick-Stations}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Simpson|first1=Bill|title=A History of the Railways of Oxfordshire; Part 1: The North|year=1997|publisher=Lamplight Publications|location=Witney|isbn=978-1-89924-602-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Stretton|first1=John|title=British Railways Past and Present: Oxfordshire; A Second Selection|id=No. 55|year=2006|publisher=Past & Present Publishing|location=Kettering|isbn=978-1-85895-203-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Waters|first1=Laurence|last2=Doyle|first2=Tony|title=British Railways Past and Present: Oxfordshire|id=No. 15|year=1992|publisher=Silver Link Publishing|location=Wadenhoe|isbn=978-0-94797-187-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Waters|first1=Laurence|title=Rail Centres: Oxford|year=1986|publisher=Ian Allan|location=Londo